passages.text: Set- up into 2Q25: Strong gross margin to support the quarter. We stay focused on sales and opex dynamics

LPP shares had a solid run over the last several months on the back of stronger than expected clothing retail sales data for Poland and the management's more positive comments about the trading environment and pricing in 2Q25 (CFO's recent interview to PAP Biznes). We expect LPP to print 2Q25 results ahead of our initial expectations and up FY25 EBITDA/EBIT/Net profit forecasts by \(4\% /7\% /8\%\) largely due to more resilient gross margin (favorable FX movement, less discounting in Sinsay where excess inventory was lost in a fire at a DC, stable competitive backdrop). That said, for us the focus in the upcoming results is on sales per store in the Sinsay format and opex dynamics as they would showcase the impact of LPP's ambitious growth strategy - a key pillar of the investment case, in our opinion. We believe that similarly to JMT (OW, covered by Borja Olcese) and DNP (N) which reported 2Q25 LFLs at the low end of the Street's expectations and in the case of DNP in particular missed on higher opex, we could see some profit- taking in LPP if sales and operating margins do not beat Consensus expectations. We continue to see risks to long- term forecasts skewed to the downside for the retailer and that the cost of Sinsay store growth (as well as cannibalization of the existing setwork) is not fully factored in by the Sell Side (we sit 12- 16% below Bloomberg consensus on 2027- 28 Net Profit). We reiterate our N rating, slightly adjust our Jan- 27 PT to PLN 15,600/sh and continue to prefer Pepco (OW).

Value creation from the Sinsay expansion is the key debate on the Street. During the 1Q25 results release, LPP downgraded the guidance for the Sinsay stores rollout (from 1,500 to 1,100) as it paused the openings of their mini format which turned out to be less successful vs. the initial plan. According to the company, it was able to open \(>250\) new Sinsay stores in 2Q and has been testing the offer mix change in the smallest stores (shifting the offer more towards clothing that accounts for \(75\%\) in the medium- sized store vs. \(50\%\) of the home assortment currently in the small stores) to improve the profitability of this format with the results yet to be announced. LPP's CFO noted in an interview that the Sinsay stores recorded positive EBITDA in 2Q after opening, close to the average for mature stores with the average payback period of 15 months, which may indicate acceleration of store growth from 2H25. Whilst we believe that LPP can execute on store openings, we also see the risk of some cannibalization of the existing network from new store growth, change in mix in favor of locations with lower store yields and higher operating costs, which tend to accompany an acceleration of space growth in retail. We thus stay focused on the dynamics in Sinsay's revenues per store and opex as \(0 / 0\) of sales in the upcoming 2Q25 results release.

Losses from the fire at the DC in Romania may be fully covered by insurance and ease the inventory pressure. While the fire at the Romanian Distribution Centre that happened at the end of June adversely affected the 2Q performance (longer delivery times to stores and some disruption in deliveries), LPP had arranged for inventory and equipment insurance as well as business interruption insurance, which would likely fully cover the losses.

Key Metrics (FYE Jan)

LPP is a pan- CEE fashion retailer focused on design, manufacturing and distribution of clothing. The company operates 2,959 stores in 40 countries and sells apparel, accessories and footwear under five brands that target different customer groups. We are cautious on LPP's store expansion program for the Sinsay brand after downgraded guidance for Sinsay mini store openings (lower- than- expected results from the format prompted a revision of the concept). We also see near- term risks to profitability stemming from higher inventory discounting and cost pressures related to store openings, which are not factored in current consensus forecasts, in our opinion. We rate LPP Neutral.
We set our Jan- 27 PT for LPP at PLN 15,600/sh, derived using a DCF model (WACC of \(11.5\%\) and \(3\%\) terminal growth rate).

At this stage LPP expects neutral impact on financials from the damage thanks to insurance coverage. At the same time, we highlight that the loss of inventory would partially offset LPP's issue with success in inventories of the Sinsay SS collection, implying a cleaner inventory set- up, which is supportive for the 2Q25 and 3Q25 gross margin outlook.

- 2Q expectations - not as bad as we initially feared expected but watch out for opex/sales dynamics as expansion accelerates. Similar to other Polish consumer companies, LPP's LFL was adversely affected by the cold weather in May (according to LPP's CFO, LFL fell 7% y/y in May). Trading environment in June and July, however, seems to have been more supportive as evidenced in the Poland clothing retail sales data and LPP's outlook for 2H25 became more positive as well, prompting us to increase both our revenue and EBITDA forecasts for 2Q25. We forecast revenue growth of 11% y/y in 2Q25 (18% adjusted for trading agents) and EBITDA uptick of 8% y/y (-53bps lower EBITDA margin yoy on the back of pressure on opex from growth). We forecast EBIT to stay largely flat y/y with net profit declining 7% y/y on higher finance costs.

- PT up by 16%, N recommendation maintained. We increase our 2025-27 estimates for LPP by 2-8% largely on the back of stronger expected gross margins and arrive at the new Jan-27 PT of PLN 15,600/sh. We continue to be on the conservative side when modelling store yields from new Sinsay stores and sit 8-11% below Bloomberg consensus on 2025-27E EBITDA for LPP, thus reiterating our N recommendation.
